answers.body_markdown:
Python uses big integers automatically. JavaScript uses floats by default, and drops to fixed-width integers for bitwise operators.

With fixed-width integers, the highest bit is designated as the sign bit. If this bit is flipped, the number is considered negative. Big integers don&#39;t have specific length, so no specific bit is designated as sign bit; so sign bit cannot be flipped by a bitwise operation or an overflow.

JavaScript does have big integers, but does not use them by default: one needs to explicitly specify they should be used, either using `BigInt` constructor, or via literals with `n` suffix:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let a = 1528001859n
    let d = 1305807872n

    a = a + d &amp; 4294967295n

    document.querySelector(&#39;span&#39;).textContent = a.toString()

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;span&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

(Stack Console does not currently support big integers, so I can&#39;t use `console.log` to print out the result directly.)

The other answer already demonstrates how to simulate the fixed-width behaviour while using big integers.

